Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"TransformationAmplitudeTable", "::", "usage"}], 
   "=", "\"\<TransformationAmplitudeTable[\[Rho]ini\[Rule]obs,events,{p,pmin,\
pmax,dp},opts] generates a table of TransformationAmplitude values, varying \
the parameter p from pmin to pmax in steps of dp. The events or any of the \
option values may depend on p. The observable obs may be a list of operators, \
in which case several tables are calculated simultaneously. The syntax \
TransformationAmplitudeTable[\[Rho]ini\[Rule]obs,events,{p,pmin,pmax,{np}},\
opts] may also be used, indicating the number of values np sampled between \
pmin and pmax.\nThe option BackgroundGenerator specifies the background \
evolution generator for the calculation. This may also depend on p.\nThe \
option EnsembleAverage may be used to specify a weighted average over an \
arbitrary variable involved in the event specifications or in any of the \
option values, including BackgroundGenerator. See the usage message for \
EnsembleAverage.\nThe option TableCoordinates specifies the point coordinates \
which are included in the output table. TableCoordinates\[Rule]<expr(p)> \
implements x-coordinates which are given by <expr(p)>, where <expr(p)> is an \
expression that depends on p, and p is the incremented parameter.\nThe output \
of TransformationAmplitudeTable with a single incremented parameter may be \
plotted directly using the ListPlot routine of Mathematica. \n\
TransformationAmplitudeTable may also employ several iterators, using syntax \
of the form \
TransformationAmplitudeTable[\[Rho]ini\[Rule]obs,events,{p1,p1min,p1max,dp1},{\
p2,p2min,p2max,dp2}..,opts]. The coordinates may then be specified using \
TableCoordinates\[Rule]{<expr(p1)>,<expr(p2)>..}. The output of \
TransformationAmplitudeTable with two iterators may be plotted directly using \
the ListContourPlot and ListDensityPlot routines.\>\""}], ";"}]], "Input",
 PageWidth:>WindowWidth,
 InitializationCell->True,
