Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Signal1D", "Subsection",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.62938461083008*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5677fffe-1f6e-448a-85a0-4b219fee311d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Signal1D", "::", "usage"}], 
   "=", "\"\<Signal1D[timing, options] simulates a 1D magnetic resonance \
signal. The parameter timing specifies the digitization of the sampled \
signal. There are several possible syntaxes for timing: (1) If timing has the \
form {tmin,tmax,\[Delta]t}, then the signal is sampled between time points \
tmin and tmax, with increments (dwell time) \[Delta]t. If tmin is omitted, \
the value 0 is used. (2) The parameter timing may also have the syntax \
{tmin,tmax,{nsample}}, where nsample is the number of sampling points in the \
interval [tmin,tmax]. The number of sampling points nsample may be an even \
integer or may  be specified using strings \\\"1k\\\", \\\"2k\\\" etc. If \
tmin is omitted, the value 0 is used. (3) timing may have the syntax {tmin,{\
\[Omega]SW,nsample}}, where \[Omega]SW is the spectral bandwidth in rad\
\[NonBreakingSpace]\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(s\), \(-1\)]\). The number of \
sampling points nsample may be an even integer, or may be specified using \
strings \\\"1k\\\", \\\"2k\\\" etc. If tmin is omitted, the value 0 is used. \
In practice, the timing syntax {{\[Omega]SW,nsample}} is often the most \
convenient.\nSignal1D[timing, evgen, options] applies an evolution generator \
evgen throughout the signal evolution, where evgen is an operator or a \
superoperator, or a time-dependent function of an operator or a \
superoperator. If evgen is absent, the default None is used, in which case \
the option BackgroundGenerator may be used to specify the Hamiltonian or \
Liouvillian under which the signal evolves.  \n\tSignal1D[timing, events, \
options] performs the specified list of events while the signal is detected \
(padding out the remaining acquisition time with None). The events argument \
may have the form Repeat[events,n] in which case a repetition of the events \
is performed at the beginning of the acquisition interval. The syntax \
Repeat[events] fills the entire signal acquisition interval with the \
appropriate number of repetitions. \nThe available options include \
InitialDensityOperator, Observable, Preparation, BackgroundGenerator, \
NormalizationFactor, SignalCalculationMethod, MatchSamplingToPeriod, \
ReportSignalCalculationMethod, LineBroadening, EnsembleAverage, \
CarouselAverage, DigitalFrequencyResolution, ZeroFill, and \
ForceEvenNumberOfPoints. The option BackgroundGenerator may be of the form \
{prepbackg,detbackg} (in case of default \\\"LeftToRight\\\" chronology), \
indicating different values of BackgroundGenerator during the Preparation \
sequence and the signal detection. \>\""}], ";"}]], "Input",
 PageWidth:>WindowWidth,
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.461322189599052*^9, 3.461322301335417*^9}, {
